ck feminist interrogation, reaching from the #MeToo movement to the legacy of gender-based violence against Black womenFrom Michelle Obama to Condoleezza Rice, Black women are uniquely scrutinized in the public eye. In Re-Imagining Black Women, Nikol G. Alexander-Floyd explores how Black women—and Blackness more broadly—are understood in our political imagination and often become the subjects of public controversy. Drawing on politics, popular culture, psychoanalysis, and more, Alexander-Floyd examines our conflicting ideas, opinions, and narratives about Black women, showing how they are equally revered and reviled as an embodiment of good and evil, cast either as victims or villains, citizens or outsiders. Ultimately, Alexander-Floyd showcases the complex experiences of Black women as political subjects. At a time of extreme racial tension, Re-Imagining Black Women provides insight into the parts that Black women play, and are expected to play, in politics and popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American womenxPolitical activity. 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aWomen, BlackxPolitical activity. 0aWomen, BlackxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aBarack Obama.  aBill Cosby.  aCondoleezza Rice.  aDiary of a Mad Black Woman.  aDominique Strauss-Kahn.  aDonald Trump.  aKamala Harris.  aKathryn Stockett.  aMadea.  aMichelle Obama.  aMoynihan report.  aObama.  aR. Kelly.  aThe Help.  aTyler Perry.  aabject.  aamerican political development.  ablack leadership.  ablack politics.  ablack studies.  ablack women.  ablackface minstrelsy.  acapitalism.  acivic membership.  acolorblind.  acoronavirus.  acovid-19.  acrash.  acritical black feminism.  adefences.  adenial.